{# ─── Chart 5 · Global Affordability ──────────────────────────────── #}
<section class="gallery-section" id="section-global-aff" aria-labelledby="title-global-aff">
    <div class="gallery-section-inner">
        <header class="gallery-section-header">
            <p class="gallery-section-eyebrow">&sect;II &middot; Real-World Denominations &middot; Chart 5 of 10</p>
            <h2 id="title-global-aff" class="gallery-section-title">Global Housing Affordability</h2>
            <p class="gallery-section-subtitle">Price-to-income ratio across major English-speaking markets, 2005&ndash;2024 &mdash; Demographia annual median surveys.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="gallery-chart-frame">
            <canvas id="galleryGlobalAffChart" aria-label="Global housing price-to-income ratios across major markets"></canvas>
            <div class="gallery-chart-fallback" aria-hidden="true">
                <p class="chart-loading">Loading the survey&hellip;</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gallery-section-prose">
            <p>Demographia tracks median home price as a multiple of median household income, every year, across major English-speaking markets. The dashed green line is the <em>3.0&times;</em> threshold they label &lsquo;affordable.&rsquo; Hong Kong has sat above 11&times; for fifteen years. Vancouver, Sydney, and Greater London cluster near or above 10&times;. The United States is closest to the threshold &mdash; and even it is comfortably above, with a clearly upward trajectory through 2021.</p>
            <p>What's remarkable about the chart isn't any one city's number &mdash; it's that <em>every market</em> shown has been judged unaffordable for the entire data window. The denominator is income, and incomes have not kept pace with housing globally for two decades.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="gallery-section-source">More in this exploration &rarr; <a href="/bitcoin-vs-real-estate.html#affordability">Bitcoin vs. Real Estate</a></p>
    </div>
</section>


{# ─── Chart 6 · BTC Needed for Retirement (decay curve) ───────────── #}
<section class="gallery-section" id="section-retirement" aria-labelledby="title-retirement">
    <div class="gallery-section-inner">
        <header class="gallery-section-header">
            <p class="gallery-section-eyebrow">&sect;II &middot; Real-World Denominations &middot; Chart 6 of 10</p>
            <h2 id="title-retirement" class="gallery-section-title">BTC Needed for Retirement, by Year</h2>
            <p class="gallery-section-subtitle">BTC required at each retirement year's Power Law trend price to fund $100K/year &mdash; 4% rule, $2.5M principal.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="gallery-chart-frame">
            <canvas id="galleryRetirementChart" aria-label="BTC needed for retirement decay curve"></canvas>
            <div class="gallery-chart-fallback" aria-hidden="true">
                <p class="chart-loading">Loading the curve&hellip;</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gallery-section-prose">
            <p>At today's Power Law trend price, you'd need roughly <em>20 BTC</em> to fund a $100K/year retirement under the 4% rule (a $2.5M nest egg). Push the retirement year out ten years, and the requirement falls to ~1.4 BTC. Twenty years, ~0.23 BTC. Thirty years, ~0.06 BTC.</p>
            <p class="prose-footnote"><em>Each anchor is its own scenario</em> &mdash; this isn't a single stack drawing down. The chart shows that as bitcoin's trend price compounds, the BTC count required to support the same lifestyle falls sharply. The math privileges patience.</p>
        </div>

        <p class="gallery-section-source">More in this exploration &rarr; <a href="/the-bitcoin-retirement.html">The Bitcoin Retirement</a></p>
    </div>
</section>


